      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm working on this embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and i'm running into a serious issue. The system has a very limited heap, and over a period of about 4-6 hours of operation, we're seeing a gradual exhaustion of available RAM. It's not a sudden crash, just a slow crawl towards an OOM state.\n\nHere is a simplified version of the telemetry processing loop where we think the issue might be:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_telemetry(const uint8_t* buffer, size_t len) {\n    TelemetryFrame* frame = new TelemetryFrame(); \n    if (deserialize(buffer, len, frame)) {\n        auto* data_point = new DataPoint(frame->timestamp, frame->value);\n        m_history.push_back(data_point);\n        \n        if (m_history.size() > MAX_HISTORY) {\n            // Potential issue area?\n            delete m_history.front();\n            m_history.erase(m_history.begin());\n        }\n    } else {\n        // If deserialization fails, we still allocated the frame\n        // but we aren't doing anything with it.\n    }\n    // Note: frame is still a pointer here\n}\n```\n\nI've checked the basic `delete` calls, but I can't find the leak. Can you give me a systematic way to approach locating exactly where this memory is escaping?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A slow, creeping memory leak in an embedded system, especially one dealing with high-frequency data like telemetry, is almost always a case of forgotten cleanup, like a lost or un-deleted heap allocation. You've got a classic \"resource management\" problem here, and I'd suggest you look at this with the mindset of a very paranoid, tiny, resource-starved goblin hoarding all the bits.\n\nFirst, let's address the immediate code snippet, because you have a definite leak there—the `TelemetryFrame* frame = new TelemetryFrame();` is never deleted if `deserialize` fails, or if the function exits early without a successful push. You must wrap that allocation in a structure that guarantees cleanup, like a `std::unique_ptr` (if your compiler/standard library supports it robustly in your constrained environment) or, more traditionally in bare-metal C++, use RAII wrappers or a `goto` cleanup block.\n\nFor the broader systematic approach, since you're on an ECU, standard debugging tools might be too heavy, so you need low-level instrumentation. You need to count the allocations and deallocations. This is where you start tracking the memory usage, not just looking",
      "source": "target",
