      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Goblin hoarding all the bits\" is just a metaphor for how tiny, greedy, and utterly obsessed with hoarding resources these little heap-scavenging beasts are! They never let go of a shiny pebble, and that's exactly what your memory leak is doing—it's hoarding RAM until the whole system chokes.\n\nSince Valgrind is too heavy, implementing a custom `operator new`/`operator delete` wrapper is the right, albeit slightly painful, path. You don't need to log *everything*; you need to log the *context* of the allocation.\n\nHere are the specific metrics you should track in your custom allocator wrapper, keeping the overhead low:\n\n1.  **Allocation Counter & Call Stack Capture (The Crucial Part):** When `new` is called, you must record the memory address, the size requested, and—most importantly—the **call stack trace** at that exact moment. This stack trace tells you *where* the allocation originated.\n2.  **Deallocation Counter:** When `delete` is called, you must look up the corresponding address in your tracking structure and remove it.\n\nTo keep the overhead low, instead of storing full, complex stack traces",
